    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Corbin Carroll** leads the charge with an elite score of 79.74. While he faces a decent arm in Pop, the convergence of his spot in the #2 hole and a favorable xwOBA environment provides the highest ceiling on the roster. **Trevor Story** (69.04) and **Josh Naylor** (68.46) represent our next tier of high-efficiency starts; **Trevor Story** benefits specifically from a sluggish opposing delivery that invites stolen base opportunities\u2014a critical lever in our pursuit of 5x5 categories\u2014while **Josh Naylor** capitalizes on a high-xERA matchup against Bolton that should yield significant counting stats.\n\nPlatoon edges are dictating much of our middle-of-the-pack construction today. **Mickey Moniak** (65.20) sees a significant boost from a +14% platoon adjustment, making him a priority play despite a middling matchup. Conversely, **Dalton Rushing** (42.58) is our most constrained starter. While his base projection is functional, he is forced to contend with an elite arm in deGrom and a #7 batting order slot that caps his RBI potential. The closest call on the bench was **Zach McKinstry** (50.08); he was evaluated aggressively due to his elite sprint speed against a high-SB-allowance pitcher in Alcantara, but he was ultimately relegated to the bench because his #8 spot in the order diluted his run-scoring probability compared to the consistency of **Tyler Soderstrom** and **Seiya Suzuki**.\n\nMonitor the conditions closely, particularly for **Seiya Suzuki**, who receives a +10% bump for wind conditions but remains a high-variance play against a sub-3.10 xERA pitcher. While we are maximizing our efficiency, keep a watchful eye on the elite pitching presence of deGrom and Woodruff. Both pitchers pose significant threats to our daily AVG floor, and while we are banking on the stolen base upside of players like **James Wood** to bridge the gap if the power numbers falter, the narrow margins in these matchups underscore the importance of our rotation strategy.",
